    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-03-31T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-03-31T17:00:00-05:00" n="719"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d719">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/583: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Nanking</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-31T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 31, 1931—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>18. For Minister Johnson: Your March 28, 10 a.m., and March 28, 4 p.m., from
                    Nanking.</p>
                <p>(1) <hi rend="italic">Transfer of jurisdiction</hi>. After the words “as regards
                    rights of appeal and in all other matters of procedure” in paragraph 2 (2), the
                    Department feels it would be desirable that there be added these words, “both
                    administrative and judicial” for the purpose of having a definite provision
                    entitling American citizens to seek redress or relief from arbitrary acts by
                    administrative officials through “administrative proceedings”.</p>
                <p>In paragraphs (3) and (4) under the same heading, there are reported provisions
                    for British subjects to be subject only to modern courts of justice and police
                    courts. On account of the frequent declarations <pb facs="0898" n="788"
                        xml:id="pg_788"/> of martial law in China, it is the belief of the
                    Department that it would be desirable to have in an exchange of notes the above
                    provisions made applicable at all times, even with martial law declared. It was
                    for this reason that the Department inserted the words “at all times” in its
                    draft of January 19.</p>
                <p>(2) <hi rend="italic">Lawyers and interpreters</hi>. Agreed minute. The
                    Department prefers having this made the subject of an exchange of notes.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
